<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

    <!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
        <handout margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="Week11Wed">
            <title>Wednesday Week 11 - Combinations of Functions</title>
<page>
        <objectives>
          <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Work with combinations of functions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Explore how relationships between functions give rise to features on the graphs of combinations.
                </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </objectives>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    Another, seemingly simpler, way of creating new functions from old ones is to <em>combine</em> using the operations of arithmetic: addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. While these constructions are simple, the way these combinations behave based on how functions relate to one another is important in many situations.
                </p>
            </introduction>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Combinations from a Table</title>
    <p></p>
    <p>
        Finding the outputs of sums, differences, products, and quotients of functions is easy; just evaluate the individual components and do the arithmetic. To see this, fill in the last four rows of the following table.
    </p>
        <tabular>
            <row header="yes" bottom="major">
                <cell><m>x</m></cell> <cell><m>-1</m></cell> <cell><m>0</m></cell> <cell><m>1</m></cell> <cell><m>2</m></cell> <cell><m>3</m></cell> <cell><m>4</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell> <cell><m>-4</m></cell> <cell><m>-1</m></cell> <cell><m>2</m></cell> <cell><m>5</m></cell> <cell><m>8</m></cell> <cell><m>11</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>g(x)</m></cell> <cell><m>4</m></cell> <cell><m>-1</m></cell> <cell><m>0</m></cell> <cell><m>-1</m></cell> <cell><m>4</m></cell> <cell><m>9</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>f(x)+g(x)</m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>2f(x)</m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>(g(x))^2</m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>\frac{g(x)}{f(x)}</m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell> <cell><m>\ \ </m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>

</paragraphs>

<p>
    Some observations:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <p>
            The product of two functions is zero if and only if one of the factors is zero.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            The difference of two functions is zero if and only if the two functions are equal.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            The quotient of two functions is zero if and only if when the numerator is zero and the denominator is not zero.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            The quotient of two functions is one if and only if the two functions are equal and not zero.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            The sign of a product or quotient is determined by the sign of the factors and/or numerator and denominator.
        </p>
    </li>
</ul>

</page>
<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Graphing Problems</title>
    <p></p>
    Use the ideas from the previous page to give rough sketches (show the important features, possibly without exact <m>y</m>-values) of the following combinations.
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>f(x) = \sin(x) - \cos(x)</m>
            </p>
                <image>
<prefigure label="trig-axes1" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(600,250)" margins="(30,5,30,5)">
  <coordinates bbox="(-2*pi-.2, -6, 2*pi+.2, 6)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x"
               h-pi-format="yes"
               hticks="(-2*pi,pi/4,2*pi)"
               hlabels="(-2*pi,pi/2,2*pi)" />
  </coordinates>
</diagram>  
</prefigure>
</image> 
        </li>

 <li>
            <p>
                <m>f(x) = \sec(x)\tan(x)</m>
            </p>
                <image>
<prefigure label="trig-axes2" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(600,250)" margins="(30,5,30,5)">
  <coordinates bbox="(-2*pi-.2, -6, 2*pi+.2, 6)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x"
               h-pi-format="yes"
               hticks="(-2*pi,pi/4,2*pi)"
               hlabels="(-2*pi,pi/2,2*pi)" />
  </coordinates>
</diagram> 
</prefigure>
</image> 
        </li>
    </ol>
</paragraphs>

</page>
<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Another Graph</title>
<p>
    
</p>
<p>
    Use the graphs of <m>y = x</m> and <m>y = \cos(x)</m> to sketch a graph of <m>f(x) = x\cos(x)</m>.
</p>

                <image>
<prefigure label="xcosx" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(500,500)" margins="(30,5,30,5)">
  <definition>g(x)=x</definition>
  <definition>f(x)=cos(x)</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-2*pi-.2, -2*pi-.2, 2*pi+.2, 2*pi+.2)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x"
               h-pi-format="yes"
               v-pi-format="yes"
               hticks="(-2*pi,pi/4,2*pi)"
               hlabels="(-2*pi,pi/2,2*pi)" />
    <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
    <graph at="graph" function="g"/>
  </coordinates>
</diagram> 
</prefigure>
</image> 

</paragraphs>   



</page>

        

</handout>
